The request uses GET with URL {{base_url}}/posts/1 and an environment where base_url=https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com. A correct Tests tab:

pm.test("status is 200", () => pm.response.to.have.status(200));
pm.test("title is present", () => {
  const body = pm.response.json();
  pm.expect(body.title).to.be.a('string').and.not.empty;
});

Both tests should pass: /posts/1 returns 200 and a non-empty title string.

example:
A valid nested JSON payload and the paths to reach its values:

```json
{
  "id": 42,
  "name": "Ann",
  "active": true,
  "middleName": null,
  "address": {
    "city": "Kyiv",
    "zip": "01001"
  },
  "orders": [
    { "orderId": 100, "total": 49.99 },
    { "orderId": 101, "total": 12.50 }
  ]
}
```

Paths: name = "Ann" (string), active = true (boolean), middleName = null, address.city = "Kyiv", orders[0].orderId = 100, orders[1].total = 12.50. Note id 42 is a number, not the string "42".
